Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.680
&gt;&gt; So, hello, everyone. Thank you all for
coming out. We are very happy to have Justin

00:00:07.680 --> 00:00:12.860
Fox here today in the office to talk about
his new book, "The Myth of the Rational Market."

00:00:12.860 --> 00:00:19.080
This is Justin's first book, but he has been
a blogger and contributor to the Times Magazine

00:00:19.080 --> 00:00:23.740
blog for--since 2007. And before that, he
worked for Fortune Magazine for over a decade.

00:00:23.740 --> 00:00:27.650
So we are very excited to have him here in
the office today. So, everyone, please welcome,

00:00:27.650 --> 00:00:32.130
Justin Fox.
&gt;&gt; FOX: And it looks like I'm going to have

00:00:32.130 --> 00:00:38.070
to stay close to this mic, so I'll like lean
on the podium. I don't know. I thought what

00:00:38.070 --> 00:00:43.180
I should do is start with a story that goes
back to my--when I was first starting out

00:00:43.180 --> 00:00:48.280
at Fortune Magazine. It kind of explains why
I ended up writing this book and why I think

00:00:48.280 --> 00:00:53.540
it matters. And, luckily, a financial crisis
happened to make lots of other people think

00:00:53.540 --> 00:00:58.620
it matters, too, but I was writing this book
long before that came along. What is was is

00:00:58.620 --> 00:01:02.110
I just got in to Fortune. I haven't been a
business journalist before. I'd just been

00:01:02.110 --> 00:01:07.320
sort of a general interest business writer.
But somehow, I ended up covering the intersection

00:01:07.320 --> 00:01:12.280
between corporations and financial markets,
corporations in Wall Street. And one of the

00:01:12.280 --> 00:01:17.749
first big stories I wrote for the magazine
was about the whole weird practice of managing

00:01:17.749 --> 00:01:23.909
earnings and managing Wall Street's consensus
earnings forecast and trying to beat the consensus

00:01:23.909 --> 00:01:29.490
by a penny. And this whole dance that developed
early in the early to mid '90s and, I mean,

00:01:29.490 --> 00:01:33.770
actually, the founders of this company made
a really big deal about not wanting to participate

00:01:33.770 --> 00:01:38.889
in that dance, but that was later. So this
was 1997, and it was very clear that there

00:01:38.889 --> 00:01:47.600
were huge amounts of effort at the CFO levels,
CEO level put into making sure that you beat

00:01:47.600 --> 00:01:53.939
the consensus earning target of all the Wall
Street analysts by at least a penny or two.

00:01:53.939 --> 00:01:58.450
And as I was--so I documented this talk people
about why they did it, and I thought it would

00:01:58.450 --> 00:02:02.709
be interesting to look at the academic literature
on this whole phenomena. And it turned out

00:02:02.709 --> 00:02:07.680
there were lots of papers by accounting professors
explaining that, yes, there was lots of evidence

00:02:07.680 --> 00:02:12.671
that companies did weird things in order to
make their quarterly earnings, first of all,

00:02:12.671 --> 00:02:18.360
come out smoothly rising over time, but, second
of all, to meet these consensus targets. But

00:02:18.360 --> 00:02:23.710
then there was this really weird thing about
all of this accounting literature is when

00:02:23.710 --> 00:02:29.000
they went around to try to explain why, they
came up with kind of weird things like maybe

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:34.300
it had something to do with their bonus structure
or maybe it was some debt covenant, but they

00:02:34.300 --> 00:02:38.790
basically weren't allowed to talk about the
sort of most obvious reason why all the CEOs

00:02:38.790 --> 00:02:43.090
thought they were managing their earnings,
which was to affect their stock price. And

00:02:43.090 --> 00:02:47.700
the reason for that was because if you were--had
a Ph.D. and got a Ph.D. in accounting in the

00:02:47.700 --> 00:02:52.610
last 25, 30 years, you were taught--because
accounting is sort of this--taught as the

00:02:52.610 --> 00:02:57.750
subset of academic finance--you were taught
that you couldn't fool the market, that as

00:02:57.750 --> 00:03:00.730
a corporate executive, you couldn't--I mean,
unless you were out right lying, but if you're

00:03:00.730 --> 00:03:05.260
using relatively transparent things like just
shoving earnings into one quarter instead

00:03:05.260 --> 00:03:08.319
of the next, that people can see through.
But that should actually have absolutely no

00:03:08.319 --> 00:03:13.739
impact on stock price and, therefore, that
can't be why anybody was doing it. And I remember

00:03:13.739 --> 00:03:17.140
that struck me as a little strange of the
time. I ended up writing the article just

00:03:17.140 --> 00:03:21.799
saying, well, maybe all these CEOs and CFOs
are crazy to be doing this. I kind of left

00:03:21.799 --> 00:03:29.790
it at that. And I came across a couple of
similar conflicts between what everybody in

00:03:29.790 --> 00:03:34.340
corporate world believed and what all these
lessons out of academic finance and accounting

00:03:34.340 --> 00:03:37.830
were. In other words, it was about stock options
accounting, which was a big, controversial

00:03:37.830 --> 00:03:42.430
thing in the late '90s. Basically, all the
accountants thought it should be accounted

00:03:42.430 --> 00:03:48.150
for as an expense. Everybody in Silicon Valley
said that would be a disaster because the

00:03:48.150 --> 00:03:51.829
feeling was somehow it would cause all the
stock prices of Silicon Valley companies to

00:03:51.829 --> 00:03:56.040
collapse. That was one--that was a bad reason,
the better reason why, it would just cause

00:03:56.040 --> 00:04:01.019
executives to give out fewer of them. So,
I did a lot of that writing. I was sort of

00:04:01.019 --> 00:04:07.489
puzzled by this lack of interest in the academe
in the thought that maybe markets weren't

00:04:07.489 --> 00:04:13.349
always--be able to see through everything.
I went away. I went to London. I was Fortune's

00:04:13.349 --> 00:04:18.739
Europe guy for a couple of years, came back
and was in the office in New York in 2002

00:04:18.739 --> 00:04:25.910
and just happened to pick up this book by
a Caltech economist, specialized in finance,

00:04:25.910 --> 00:04:31.440
where I just sort of leafing through, I realize
he was saying that actually he didn't believe

00:04:31.440 --> 00:04:36.330
anymore that markets could see every--see
through everything and were perfectly efficient.

00:04:36.330 --> 00:04:40.580
And very quickly, as I started looking through,
I realized right around when I'd written that

00:04:40.580 --> 00:04:46.140
first article for Fortune in '97, there had
been this big shift in academic finance. There

00:04:46.140 --> 00:04:52.520
were lots of people questioning whether something
like the tech stock bubble of 1999 and 2000

00:04:52.520 --> 00:04:58.169
could be explained by anything other than
just people going a bit nuts. And that struck

00:04:58.169 --> 00:05:01.159
me as a good idea for an article, wrote an
article for Fortune called--I think it was

00:05:01.159 --> 00:05:07.580
called, "Is the Market Rational? No, But Neither
Are You, So Don't Think You Can Beat It."

00:05:07.580 --> 00:05:11.990
It was a very investing focus because it was
a foreign investor guide. And then that led

00:05:11.990 --> 00:05:16.750
to this book. Some guy from a publisher, Harper-Collins
came and said I should write a book about

00:05:16.750 --> 00:05:20.710
that and nobody had ever--from a reputable
publisher had ever asked me to that before,

00:05:20.710 --> 00:05:25.030
and, so, I said yes, which is something I
regretted greatly over many of the last five

00:05:25.030 --> 00:05:32.410
or six years. But it's okay now. And what
I--so what I thought is I don't want to write

00:05:32.410 --> 00:05:37.389
this polemic. I just want to the story of
why did all these accounting professors and

00:05:37.389 --> 00:05:42.199
finance professors and a lot of economists
come to believe that financial markets, the

00:05:42.199 --> 00:05:47.000
stock market in particular, were so smart
and able to see through everything and not

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:54.090
subject to bubbles and everything else. And
the story I came up with is it was this combination

00:05:54.090 --> 00:05:58.590
of things. I mean, there are certain elements
that have been there in economics forever

00:05:58.590 --> 00:06:02.280
because there are certain elements of truth
to it. Markets are smart. They react to things.

00:06:02.280 --> 00:06:07.510
They can see through people's nonsense sometimes.
And the whole idea of Adam Smith's invisible

00:06:07.510 --> 00:06:14.449
hand of market forces moving things in relatively
positive direction without--because of the

00:06:14.449 --> 00:06:18.740
actions of lots of selfish people looking
out for themselves, that's been around forever,

00:06:18.740 --> 00:06:25.009
but we've developed after World War II was
this combination of, first, it was the rise

00:06:25.009 --> 00:06:30.070
of statistics and mathematical modeling, not
just in economics but all over the corporate

00:06:30.070 --> 00:06:34.629
America and a lot of that, I mean, it was
partly because of advances in statistics.

00:06:34.629 --> 00:06:42.150
A lot of it was just because World War II,
the experience. I mean, U.S. and U.K. used

00:06:42.150 --> 00:06:46.419
statistical thinking in a way that the Axis
Powers did not. And it really helped. They

00:06:46.419 --> 00:06:51.350
called this operations research. It was the
term [INDISTINCT] for what they were in general

00:06:51.350 --> 00:06:57.379
doing. And a lot of economists were involved.
Milton Friedman spent part of World War II

00:06:57.379 --> 00:07:02.199
helped--helping working at this statistics
office at Columbia University, helping figure

00:07:02.199 --> 00:07:08.500
out things like how many pieces you want to
score in artillery shell into--so, to determine

00:07:08.500 --> 00:07:13.470
whether it blows up into lots of little pieces
or just a few big ones. And it's a risk [INDISTINCT]

00:07:13.470 --> 00:07:18.080
thing. If it's the big pieces, they cause
more damage if they hit. If it's the little

00:07:18.080 --> 00:07:23.090
pieces, they are more likely to hit but they
cause less damage if they hit. And during--in

00:07:23.090 --> 00:07:26.970
the middle of the Battle of the Bulge, they
were actually gunnery officers who flew back

00:07:26.970 --> 00:07:32.610
to Washington to consult with Milton Friedman
about what to do, which obviously gave him

00:07:32.610 --> 00:07:37.960
and other economist a certain confidence in
what they could do with these tools. So, there

00:07:37.960 --> 00:07:42.919
was that. There was the collapse of what had
been for awhile there on the first part of

00:07:42.919 --> 00:07:47.740
the century in the U.S., kind of the dominant
economic tradition, which was they called

00:07:47.740 --> 00:07:53.050
themselves institutionalists, mostly. And,
really, the guy now who most of us remember

00:07:53.050 --> 00:07:57.150
who was part of this tradition is John Kenneth
Galbraith, but it's sort of this historical,

00:07:57.150 --> 00:08:03.740
literary way of looking at economics that's
very appealing to journalists like me, but

00:08:03.740 --> 00:08:10.650
totally had no answers during the Great Depression.
And so people started looking to people like

00:08:10.650 --> 00:08:14.500
John Maynard Keynes, who really was a more
conventional economist who was just willing

00:08:14.500 --> 00:08:18.919
to have different ideas. And then the other
part of it was just sort of political waves.

00:08:18.919 --> 00:08:25.410
There were these beginnings of a libertarian
backlash against the New Deal and Great Society

00:08:25.410 --> 00:08:31.600
and all of these programs. And so these things
all came together at Chicago and at MIT. And

00:08:31.600 --> 00:08:38.430
at MIT the focus was on statistics and the
math and this idea that randomness was this

00:08:38.430 --> 00:08:42.512
really important concept to understanding
pretty much everything that goes on in the

00:08:42.512 --> 00:08:48.800
world. And it is in so many things. And it
sort of came about as this way to tweak all

00:08:48.800 --> 00:08:55.440
these people who thought you could stock charts
and divine truth out of the fact that over

00:08:55.440 --> 00:09:00.180
the past 40 years, if you have like head and
shoulders is one thing, that that will lead

00:09:00.180 --> 00:09:06.510
to some result afterwards. And what a lot
of statisticians and economists from the '30s

00:09:06.510 --> 00:09:10.610
and to the '50s were able to show is you could
create all those same patterns with random

00:09:10.610 --> 00:09:17.110
processes. So, there was that coming out of
MIT, which was basically market movements

00:09:17.110 --> 00:09:22.910
are akin to random movements, they're really
to predict. I mean, maybe you can--maybe some

00:09:22.910 --> 00:09:27.790
people can, but, in general, there's no easy
picking in the stock market. That came together

00:09:27.790 --> 00:09:34.230
with Chicago where everybody agreed with that
but gave it this more ideological phrase where

00:09:34.230 --> 00:09:41.480
it became this idea that, "Well, if markets
were perfectly, rationally reflecting all

00:09:41.480 --> 00:09:46.410
available information that's out there, then
their movements would be random because they'd

00:09:46.410 --> 00:09:53.040
just be reflecting--I mean, news is random,
so they would be reflecting changes in news,

00:09:53.040 --> 00:09:58.279
changes in risk assessment to a certain extent,
but there would be no really to detect patterns

00:09:58.279 --> 00:10:02.790
in them. So, the idea of a rational market
would be a random market. Market seemed to

00:10:02.790 --> 00:10:07.380
be pretty random; therefore, markets must
be rational. And that led to this whole research

00:10:07.380 --> 00:10:14.300
project at Chicago of finding evidence that
market, the stock market in particular, was

00:10:14.300 --> 00:10:20.380
really doing a great job of assigning prices
to things. And in one line of research was

00:10:20.380 --> 00:10:24.280
just looking at mutual fund performance and
finding that mutual funds as a group didn't

00:10:24.280 --> 00:10:29.300
beat the market. And, now, that seems kind
of obvious because mutual funds are such a

00:10:29.300 --> 00:10:32.350
big part of the market, and I think that was
part of the explanation for why they did it

00:10:32.350 --> 00:10:38.190
in the '60s either. But the idea up to then,
the stock market investing was dominated by

00:10:38.190 --> 00:10:42.600
individual investors so the [INDISTINCT] more
professionals are going to do better than

00:10:42.600 --> 00:10:46.700
them. And here are a bunch of highly-paid
professionals as a group, especially when

00:10:46.700 --> 00:10:52.139
you adjust for their volatility of their performance;
they didn't do any better than the market.

00:10:52.139 --> 00:10:57.970
So that was one bit of evidence. Another bit
was that prices reacted really swiftly to

00:10:57.970 --> 00:11:02.170
new information. Often, new information that
hadn't been publicly disclosed, markets could

00:11:02.170 --> 00:11:08.710
sniff it out. And, again, these are all valid
points and--but it kind of came together into

00:11:08.710 --> 00:11:15.410
this all-encompassing view of the world that,
basically--I mean, the simplest way to put

00:11:15.410 --> 00:11:19.950
it is "the price is right." And there actually
was a professor at the University of Rochester,

00:11:19.950 --> 00:11:25.070
which was sort of University of Chicago junior
in the 1970s, who would start his classes

00:11:25.070 --> 00:11:31.550
by yelling, "The price is right! The price
is right!" So, that was the belief. And there

00:11:31.550 --> 00:11:35.900
was this side element that seemed to come
attached to all of these, and it doesn't have

00:11:35.900 --> 00:11:40.680
to be--and these don't have to go together,
but, I guess, because all these people were

00:11:40.680 --> 00:11:45.730
saying that, "OK, markets are unpredictable.
We can't predict prices. Nobody can predict

00:11:45.730 --> 00:11:49.430
prices," but they still want to give people
something useful. What they said is, "Well,

00:11:49.430 --> 00:11:53.930
we can't predict price movements, but we can
say something about the riskiness of a particular

00:11:53.930 --> 00:12:00.310
security." And, for the most part, they just
measured riskiness as volatility. I mean,

00:12:00.310 --> 00:12:05.839
they came up with more convoluted ways. And
so coming out of this, here's this bunch of

00:12:05.839 --> 00:12:11.690
people, young finance professors from Chicago
and MIT and increasingly elsewhere--Berkley,

00:12:11.690 --> 00:12:19.950
Stanford, UCLA was a real hotbed as well--coming
along in the '70s who had this pretty clear

00:12:19.950 --> 00:12:26.920
view of how the world worked. And it was one
in which there was no point in sneaking around

00:12:26.920 --> 00:12:32.850
trying to figure out which particular stock
to buy and beat the market that way. There

00:12:32.850 --> 00:12:37.720
was a lot of point in owning stocks because
over time I did lots of historical research

00:12:37.720 --> 00:12:41.649
that had performed really well over time,
and there was an explanation for that. It

00:12:41.649 --> 00:12:46.959
was because they were riskier over short periods
and, therefore, over time that should reward

00:12:46.959 --> 00:12:53.600
you. And so that's my method of rational market.
That's--it probably--it peaked between about

00:12:53.600 --> 00:12:59.770
the--in academia--between the late '60s and
early '80s. And what sort of impact did it

00:12:59.770 --> 00:13:03.839
have? Well, the--I mean, some of the first
things that came from these people were all

00:13:03.839 --> 00:13:10.130
these measurements of investing performance
that--like the sharp ratio, alpha, et cetera.

00:13:10.130 --> 00:13:13.970
They're really big in the institutional investing
world, but they find their way into other

00:13:13.970 --> 00:13:18.589
things like Morning Star ratings and stuff
like that. The second thing was index funds

00:13:18.589 --> 00:13:23.579
which--I love index funds and I think they're
great things for lots of reasons, and you

00:13:23.579 --> 00:13:27.529
don't have to believe markets are efficient
or rational to think an index fund is a good

00:13:27.529 --> 00:13:32.361
idea, but I don't think index funds would
have happened in the '70s. The first one in

00:13:32.361 --> 00:13:37.200
an institutional level was right around the
corner here at what was then Wells Fargo Global

00:13:37.200 --> 00:13:41.440
Investors, it became Barclays Global Investors.
I don't know if it has become BlackRock Global

00:13:41.440 --> 00:13:46.230
Investors now or what, but it's going to be
global investors. And then Vanguard--Jack

00:13:46.230 --> 00:13:53.540
Vogel invented--well, created the first index
fund for retail investors a few years later.

00:13:53.540 --> 00:13:57.380
Option pricing models and the rise of derivatives
markets, again, it could have happened without

00:13:57.380 --> 00:14:02.079
this belief that prices are rational, but
it makes a lot more sense to believe in an

00:14:02.079 --> 00:14:06.980
option pricing formula which is based on existing
prices of the underlying securities, if you

00:14:06.980 --> 00:14:14.009
believe those existing prices mean something.
So, that was led to that. In the law, there

00:14:14.009 --> 00:14:19.230
was huge transformation of thinking about
corporate information disclosure and lots

00:14:19.230 --> 00:14:23.649
of other things because of this idea that
markets are really efficient. And then in

00:14:23.649 --> 00:14:30.149
terms of deregulation, clearly, this thing
he played a role in it, but a lot of the financial

00:14:30.149 --> 00:14:34.889
regulations that fell apart in the '70s just
fell apart because they weren't designed to

00:14:34.889 --> 00:14:40.200
cope with inflation and you had things like
Reg. Q that said you could only pay whatever

00:14:40.200 --> 00:14:44.149
was 5 percent on the savings account. It didn't
work very well when inflation was 10 percent.

00:14:44.149 --> 00:14:49.779
So, I don't want to give too much credit to
this myth in all of the changes that happened,

00:14:49.779 --> 00:14:56.019
but the thing that definitely did happen starting
in the '70s was this sort of "financialization

00:14:56.019 --> 00:15:00.220
of American life" where financial markets
came to play a bigger role. People, instead

00:15:00.220 --> 00:15:04.220
of having their money in a bank, they have
it in a market account. And then, increasingly,

00:15:04.220 --> 00:15:08.660
instead of having money in a pension, they
had it in a Farrow and Kaye (ph) Mutual Funds.

00:15:08.660 --> 00:15:12.519
And, again, this happened for lots of reasons
outside of what a bunch of professors at Chicago

00:15:12.519 --> 00:15:17.570
said. But this whole idea that markets are
these great rational things made it a lot

00:15:17.570 --> 00:15:24.040
more palatable, made this a popular thing.
Now, what's interesting is right about in

00:15:24.040 --> 00:15:30.320
the early '80s, the first young professors
looking to raise some hell started raising

00:15:30.320 --> 00:15:35.610
their hands, and Bob Sheller, who's now a
familiar face with his floppy hair on TV and

00:15:35.610 --> 00:15:41.730
everywhere else, he's a Yale economist and
a prolific author--he wrote a paper that,

00:15:41.730 --> 00:15:46.500
I think, was published in '81, and he was
sort of raising a hand, "Yes, but..." And

00:15:46.500 --> 00:15:52.529
it was, gee, it looked like the movements
of stock prices were a whole lot more volatile

00:15:52.529 --> 00:15:57.940
than any--and the particular thing he picked
was the dividends that were subsequently paid,

00:15:57.940 --> 00:16:01.450
but lots of other people did research with
just about every other fundamental variable

00:16:01.450 --> 00:16:07.410
you can come up with, and it was clear that
the market's movements were much more volatile.

00:16:07.410 --> 00:16:12.480
And then another guy who is sort of prominent
these days, Larry Summers, who is a young

00:16:12.480 --> 00:16:18.880
economist at Harvard--well, initially, MIT
then Harvard at that time. He did this paper

00:16:18.880 --> 00:16:27.390
sort of showing that it was impossible to
tell a rationally unpredictable market from

00:16:27.390 --> 00:16:34.399
an irrationally unpredictable market unless
you had, I think it was a 150 years of data.

00:16:34.399 --> 00:16:38.350
And so it was just basically the point that,
you know, maybe the market is random, which

00:16:38.350 --> 00:16:47.000
means prices are rational, but maybe not.
Nobody knows. And so as the years went by,

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:52.810
more and more of these ideas that everybody
was so sure about in the '50s and '60s got

00:16:52.810 --> 00:16:58.420
taken apart in academic finance. But the interesting
thing that was going on in the wider world

00:16:58.420 --> 00:17:05.290
is the 1990s were happening. And in sort of
the popular world, in the popular press, in

00:17:05.290 --> 00:17:10.810
corporate America and everywhere else, markets
seemed to be working really well. And it wasn't

00:17:10.810 --> 00:17:14.510
just the fall of the Berlin Wall and all of
that. It was that compared to what, say, the

00:17:14.510 --> 00:17:19.970
German or Japanese economy, which were these
very bank-dominated, don't-rely-on-the-price-is-set

00:17:19.970 --> 00:17:25.030
in financial markets to determine all that
much, they were struggling. The U.S. and the

00:17:25.030 --> 00:17:31.400
U.K. were doing great. And so--and these fascinating
things happened. Like Larry Summers, who had

00:17:31.400 --> 00:17:37.460
been this huge critic of financial markets
in the '80s was suddenly working first at

00:17:37.460 --> 00:17:42.721
the World Bank, then at the Clinton administration,
basically saying, well, you know, they're

00:17:42.721 --> 00:17:48.052
flawed but they work a whole lot better than
anything else. And I guess one way to look

00:17:48.052 --> 00:17:52.310
at it is Milton Friedman talked about--he
had this famous line about monetary policy

00:17:52.310 --> 00:17:57.600
like Fed decisions, they have effect on the
real economy with long and variable lags.

00:17:57.600 --> 00:18:03.820
And I think the same--the same is true of
ideas, intellectual ideas that come out of

00:18:03.820 --> 00:18:09.110
universities and elsewhere is they're starting
to have their impact on a popular culture

00:18:09.110 --> 00:18:16.150
years after they did on campus. And I just--I
mean another classic thing in the '90s, is,

00:18:16.150 --> 00:18:22.820
before the 1990s, if people were talking how
big a company was, it was always its revenue

00:18:22.820 --> 00:18:27.140
or its profits. And those are both flawed
measures, all agree. But in the '90s, it switched

00:18:27.140 --> 00:18:31.180
completely to you just talk about the market
gap and that tells you everything. And, again,

00:18:31.180 --> 00:18:36.450
it is moral encompassing, but as we learned
at the end of the '90s, it can give you some

00:18:36.450 --> 00:18:42.680
kind of weird measures of who is important
and who is not, so, which bring us all to

00:18:42.680 --> 00:18:48.490
then to kind of "what went wrong?" And--I
mean, clearly the simplest thing of what went

00:18:48.490 --> 00:18:53.310
wrong is lots of people were given mortgages
that there's no way they could have afford

00:18:53.310 --> 00:18:59.820
to pay back unless housing prices kept rising.
And the sort of more complicated--I mean,

00:18:59.820 --> 00:19:05.400
I was just trying to come up with the one--one
line explanation is that the markets for mortgage

00:19:05.400 --> 00:19:10.550
securities failed to price--they failed the
price risk. And what it turned out to be,

00:19:10.550 --> 00:19:15.380
and I think the problem that financial markets
have is they really did it differentiating

00:19:15.380 --> 00:19:19.710
like the riskiness of the two different companies,
of comparing two different companies, even

00:19:19.710 --> 00:19:25.290
different industries. What they're really
bad at is--and it's understandable--is gauging

00:19:25.290 --> 00:19:30.600
the risk that they themselves create. And
I think that's what happened in the mortgage

00:19:30.600 --> 00:19:35.810
market is that the increasingly lax lending
standards. I mean, obviously some of this

00:19:35.810 --> 00:19:41.820
was brought on by regulatory decisions and
the sort of obsession in Washington with people

00:19:41.820 --> 00:19:45.950
owning homes, but in the end they were for
the most part private investors around the

00:19:45.950 --> 00:19:50.400
world buying these mortgage securities, and
they were buying them for way too cheap, given

00:19:50.400 --> 00:19:57.580
how risky they were. And the thing about that
is that happens. It's happened again and again

00:19:57.580 --> 00:20:03.270
throughout history, that these moments have
come when people decide to just utterly ignore

00:20:03.270 --> 00:20:07.710
the potential riskiness of things and just
look only at potential returns. And so you

00:20:07.710 --> 00:20:15.410
can't blame that on this myth of the rational
market. What you can say though is that regulators

00:20:15.410 --> 00:20:21.090
and bankers and homebuyers and a lot of other
people were sort of singularly unprepared

00:20:21.090 --> 00:20:27.900
for what happened because of the dominance
of this view of financial markets in which

00:20:27.900 --> 00:20:34.560
things always happen. Prices always move for
a reason and price movements are commonly

00:20:34.560 --> 00:20:40.940
rational enough to be accounted for in pretty
simple risk models. And that's kind of where

00:20:40.940 --> 00:20:47.580
we are now. And I don't--again, this book
I've written is--it's a story about where

00:20:47.580 --> 00:20:52.620
these ideas came from, where the challengers
came from, and the sort of muddle we're in

00:20:52.620 --> 00:20:59.130
right now. I haven't written the answer, and
I don't think anybody has it at the moment.

00:20:59.130 --> 00:21:05.260
One of the issues is just because markets
are flawed and have these bubbles and panics

00:21:05.260 --> 00:21:09.720
and crashes, it doesn't mean that you're going
to come up with some government regulators

00:21:09.720 --> 00:21:15.680
who do things better. And in fact one of the
problematic things I think about especially

00:21:15.680 --> 00:21:20.870
banking regulation is there was this movement
over the past decade or two to have more flexible

00:21:20.870 --> 00:21:26.200
banking regulation, give regulators more leeway
to do what they think, they thought was right,

00:21:26.200 --> 00:21:32.810
but they caught up in all the same craziness
that markets do. So, the two things that keep

00:21:32.810 --> 00:21:38.600
coming to mind is, one, this financial market
bubbles seem to cause a lot more damage when

00:21:38.600 --> 00:21:43.720
they're built on debt rather than equity.
So you had the '90s tech stock bubble which--I

00:21:43.720 --> 00:21:47.090
mean, it caused a lot of damage in the Bay
Area but it wasn't this economic disaster

00:21:47.090 --> 00:21:52.060
because for the most part people were putting
up money that they had no contractual right

00:21:52.060 --> 00:21:59.180
to get back. They were willing to take that
risk, whereas with the mortgages and housing,

00:21:59.180 --> 00:22:04.200
it was much more debt-fueled bubble and, you
know, people have contracts. They're supposed

00:22:04.200 --> 00:22:09.170
to get paid. Those break down, you start having
all these big troubles in the financial system.

00:22:09.170 --> 00:22:14.140
So, clearly, some limitations of leverage
in boom times make sense. I don't know what

00:22:14.140 --> 00:22:20.880
that limitation ought to be. And then--but
the other obvious thing is markets are these--financial

00:22:20.880 --> 00:22:27.260
markets, in particular, are just spectacularly
efficient institution, but it's a really bad

00:22:27.260 --> 00:22:31.470
idea to have a society that's entirely run
by them. And I'm not saying we did exactly,

00:22:31.470 --> 00:22:36.580
but there were times in the late '90s when
it—-we seemed to be coming close. It's—-there

00:22:36.580 --> 00:22:43.290
is a reason why we have these obviously less
efficient but at least different bodies from

00:22:43.290 --> 00:22:50.060
charitable organizations to religious ones
to corporations themselves to governments.

00:22:50.060 --> 00:22:55.410
Diversity brings better answers for the most
part, and I think diversity of sort of the

00:22:55.410 --> 00:23:00.230
structure of economic institutions is part
of that. So that's where I am now in the story.

