numbers, and he looks at the stock price,
and if the market is undervalued and the company

00:35:50.550 --> 00:35:55.650
[INDISTINCT] buys it. Is it really that easy?
Or are you saying that the numbers are irrational

00:35:55.650 --> 00:36:00.730
and shouldn't be trusting him like that?
&gt;&gt; FOX: If--I mean, easy, I don't know, but

00:36:00.730 --> 00:36:06.711
I think it's that simple in the sense that
that's one of the--I talked about Larry Summers

00:36:06.711 --> 00:36:11.720
and Bob Schuler, but one of the other interesting
things that happened in the late '80s and

00:36:11.720 --> 00:36:18.090
early '90s is this research by a lot of sort
of hardcore orthodox finance professors, including

00:36:18.090 --> 00:36:22.700
Eugene Fama, the guy who authored the original
efficient market hypothesis, well, basically

00:36:22.700 --> 00:36:28.460
showed that over time value stocks win, value
stocks outperform the market. And a lot of

00:36:28.460 --> 00:36:33.140
the--this sort of orthodox finance crew has
struggled with that and the explanation Fama

00:36:33.140 --> 00:36:37.850
gives is it's because somehow the value stocks
are riskier therefore they're going to do

00:36:37.850 --> 00:36:43.800
better. I think, an equally good argument
is that value investing is riskier, especially

00:36:43.800 --> 00:36:48.780
if you're a professional investor, because
if you're an agent for somebody else's money,

00:36:48.780 --> 00:36:53.430
then exactly when should you be staying out
of stocks is when everybody wants to get into

00:36:53.430 --> 00:36:58.040
stocks and exactly when you should be getting
in is when everybody wants to get out. And

00:36:58.040 --> 00:37:03.370
the genius of Buffet is he set up his business
where he's not dependent on anybody else's

00:37:03.370 --> 00:37:07.660
money. He just all these companies that have
nice cash flow and he has to invest that however

00:37:07.660 --> 00:37:12.300
he wants. It doesn't matter what Richard Hathaway
stock price is. Everybody can abandoned him.

00:37:12.300 --> 00:37:17.160
He still has the cash to invest whenever he
wants to. So, I think the big reason value

00:37:17.160 --> 00:37:21.590
investing works is it's hard especially for
professionals. It's actually one of those

00:37:21.590 --> 00:37:26.870
things that might be easier for individual
investors if they have the right mental framework

00:37:26.870 --> 00:37:37.520
to be able to deal. Anything else? Yeah?
&gt;&gt; I spent a lot of times working with Wal-Mart

00:37:37.520 --> 00:37:42.790
and their betting the farm on this newly frugal
customers, and their hypothesis goes something

00:37:42.790 --> 00:37:50.680
like, you know, "we've hit a permanent reset
button, people will rethink value, will rethink

00:37:50.680 --> 00:37:55.950
the shopping experience" and, certainly, they're
