00:38:07.860 --> 00:38:13.690
you believe that? There's a lot been written
about that. And if you do or don't, what does

00:38:13.690 --> 00:38:18.570
that mean for the markets? And what does it
mean for stocks like Wal-Mart and others?

00:38:18.570 --> 00:38:25.560
&gt;&gt; FOX: First of all, I do believe it. But
everybody was saying the same thing, although

00:38:25.560 --> 00:38:30.930
probably to some lesser extent in the early
'90s. There was just a meeting the other day

00:38:30.930 --> 00:38:36.250
at Time and someone was reminding us although
we had cover story and like 1991 or 1992 about

00:38:36.250 --> 00:38:41.430
the new frugality, I think this was a bigger
crisis, people are in more financial trouble.

00:38:41.430 --> 00:38:47.870
It's more likely to actually stick. And to
use a little Google Wisdom of Crowds, I watch

00:38:47.870 --> 00:38:53.220
the little top 10 blog post on time.com all
the time, see how I'm doing, and there's this

00:38:53.220 --> 00:38:57.040
brand new blogger we've got who we haven't
given any special publicity to or anything.

00:38:57.040 --> 00:39:01.340
He's some guy living out in the woods in New
