00:39:01.340 --> 00:39:06.760
it's like six out of the ten top posts are
invariably his posts, just saying, you know,

00:39:06.760 --> 00:39:14.910
can you eat well on $50 a week, et cetera.
So, in terms of what that affects, I mean,

00:39:14.910 --> 00:39:20.920
I think at one level, companies that cater
to that to a very value oriented audience

00:39:20.920 --> 00:39:26.120
do better. At the other level, it just seems
to me that you're not going to have--you are

00:39:26.120 --> 00:39:31.720
going to have this long period of indebtedness
either shrinking or not growing very much

00:39:31.720 --> 00:39:40.270
at all. And if you look at over from early
1980s until now, or especially until like

00:39:40.270 --> 00:39:46.290
five or ten years ago, a lot of the rise in
corporate profitability and in stock prices

00:39:46.290 --> 00:39:50.700
had at least or partly be related to people
taking on more debt and spending more. And

00:39:50.700 --> 00:39:56.950
so if that's not there, that's something that
weighs on financial markets overall I would

00:39:56.950 --> 00:40:00.210
think. I mean, it's a healthy development,
but it means that you don't automatically

00:40:00.210 --> 00:40:08.120
get a booming stock market out of it. Yep?
&gt;&gt; I was interested in your views on loss

00:40:08.120 --> 00:40:12.880
aversion and how you think that skews individual
and institutional investment decisions?

00:40:12.880 --> 00:40:18.200
&gt;&gt; FOX: That, I mean, interesting, when I
started writing this book, I thought it would

00:40:18.200 --> 00:40:25.101
be this history of first the rise of this
hyper-rational view of markets and investing

00:40:25.101 --> 00:40:29.610
and then its replacement by behavioral finance
and behavioral economics and all these ideas

00:40:29.610 --> 00:40:36.310
like loss aversion that, basically, instead
of just sort of rationally looking at all

00:40:36.310 --> 00:40:43.180
possibilities and weighing the risks, you
are much more concerned about going back from

00:40:43.180 --> 00:40:50.240
your current state than weighing equally whether
you're back or forward. So, clearly, it affects

00:40:50.240 --> 00:40:55.070
individual decision-making. And, I mean, at
the institutional level, I'm sure it's there.

00:40:55.070 --> 00:40:58.510
I think there are so many other interesting
factors at the institutional level because

00:40:58.510 --> 00:41:02.840
of the added complication of being an agent
and having customers that you are working

00:41:02.840 --> 00:41:10.540
for. The thing that's difficult though is
finding ways that that's reflected in prices.

00:41:10.540 --> 00:41:15.410
And that's been one of the really interesting
things that basically behavioral finance is

00:41:15.410 --> 00:41:20.190
brought--given all these great answers about
how you could better structure a 401K program

00:41:20.190 --> 00:41:25.380
or just how individuals should think about
investing. It hasn't really delivered much

00:41:25.380 --> 00:41:30.390
of all on why prices do what they do and that
leads a lot the kind of old guard finance

00:41:30.390 --> 00:41:35.830
people to say, oh, we won. And it's not only
that, it's just--we've got this model when

00:41:35.830 --> 00:41:40.180
there's no perfect clear model that explains
everything. There are just different explanation

00:41:40.180 --> 00:41:52.180
for different things. Anything else? Yep?
